description.text:
OpenForge
=========
This Stone Edge Arch Doorway tile was designed to be compatible with Dwarven Forge dungeon tiles. To assemble, you will need approximately 20 gauge wire, or a thick paperclip. If using a paperclip, straighten and poke through the hole, then clip. Then glue the door around the paperclip, using it as a hinge.
Compatible tiles/walls in this series are tagged with OpenForge
You can find this set on github
OpenForge Sets
=============
  • Smooth Tile Series - Smooth tiles that can be used as concrete, dirt, ice, etc.
  • Smooth Edge Tile Series - Smooth tiles that can be used as concrete, dirt, ice, etc. Edge tiles.
  • Stone Tile Series - Stone tiles.
  • Stone Edge Tile Series - Stone edge tiles.
  • Crenelated Tile Series - Crenelated Tiles
  • Crenelated Edge Tile Series - Crenelated edge tiles
  • Tudor Tile Series - Tudor tiles.
  • Tudor Edge Tile Series - Tudor edge tiles.
  • Ruined Series - Ruined stone walls
  • Accessories - Pillars, etc.
  • Non-Series Tiles - Misc tiles, such as the pool
  • Module Specific Tiles - Tiles designed for specific modules.

Assembly To assemble, you will need approximately 20 gauge wire, or a thick paperclip. If using a paperclip, straighten and poke through the hole, then clip. Then glue the door around the paperclip, using it as a hinge. Painting I strongly suggest painting before assembling. For the doorway, Painting was done in 4 layers.
  • Paint whole piece in black
  • Heavily dry brush with a dark grey
  • pick at least one other color (that could be stone) and paint some random stones, front and back.
  • dry brush with grey mixed with a little olive
  • lightly dry brush with a light grey, focusing most heavily on edges
    • For the doors:
  • Paint black
  • Heavily dry brush with a dark brown
  • Dry brush with a lighter brown like burnt umber
  • Dry brush lightly with a tan
  • Use a steel or silver metal paint on the handles and bolts

description.text:
Space is a luxury in my small apartment, and even more so on my overcrowded work table. I created Firestand to hold my 13â€ MacBook Pro on top of my M-Audio FireWire 610 audio interface, It has helped me reclaim over 67 square inches of space on my desk (and, yes this is an accurate calculation of my space savings).
This is a DIY project that can be recreated using a laser cutter. All you need is a 12â€ x 24â€ piece of plexi (1/4â€œ thick), acrylic cement, and a few hours of spare time. Production files are available in Adobe Illustrator, svg, and dwg formats.

It's easy to make your own firestand. All you have to do is laser cut the parts on 12" x 24" piece of acrylic (1/4" thick). Then use an acrylic cement (such as weld-on) to glue it all together. 
Before laser cutting the parts I recommend that you measure the actual thickness of your acrylic panel in order to adjust the size of the connectors, if necessary. I find that most of the 1/4" acrylic I purchase in NY is slightly thinner than advertised. Therefore, the connecting holes on this design have been set to 0.22" wide (which on the laser I use cuts at about 0.23-0.24").

Designed a new X-Carriage for the Prusa Rework (1.0 or 1.5), meant to be used with the longer LM8LUU linear bearings (8x15x45mm). You can optionally use this with 4 x LM8UU bearings, but they'll stick out a few mm. The carriage block is designed to be strong, yet simple. The bearings are press-fit into the holes, and then (optionally) retained by 4 x M3-10mm screws and M3 washers. You'll need to take apart your X and Z axis to install this. The back of the block has recessed holes for the socket head cap screws. You will need: 4 x M4-30mm socket head cap screws, to mount the extruder.
2 x M3-20mm socket head cap screws, to attach the X-axis belt. The 2x M3 screws are used to secure the ends of the X-carriage belt: At each end of the belt, form a loop with the teeth facing in - the length of the loop should be about 18-20mm. description.text:
There are 15 polyhedral forms in the cubic system. Most are Platonic or Catalan polyhedra (but not necessarily canonical) and 5 are unusual and appear in one or two of the cubic system classes These are : deltoid dodecahedron (aka rhombdodecahedron) in class 23
pentagonal dodecahedron(aka pyritohedron) in class m3 and 23
diakisdodecahedron (aka diploid) in class m3
pentagonal icositetrahedron (aka gyroid) in class 432
tetrahedral pentagonal dodecahedron(aka tetaroid) in class 23 The STL has been generated by an openSCAD script in which the shapes are defined by Miller indices. The same script can also create crystals in the cubic system from a description of the forms and their distances. Boracite is one such example. The object may need re-orienting onto a face for printing. see my blog for further details http://kitwallace.tumblr.com/post/130274180189/forms-and-crystals-in-the-cubic-system openSCAD code is on gitHub but is work in progress. https://github.com/KitWallace/openscad/blob/master/miller.scad There is a customizer to create any of the 15 forms. Due to the method of construction, the preview is a bit small.

description.text:
After installing my Bosch palm router on my machine, I soon realized that the dust needed to be under control. I used the offset dimensions from the vac attachment that PCFlyer had, but needed a 1.25" diameter for my shop vac. For my 1st test I used some clear packing tape added around the dust shield to go almost to the surface. My long term plan is to use some material around it, maybe attached with elastic or something. I put a before and after photo to show how much more dust it picked up than my 1st attempt (that only picked up a very small percentage). This design uses 3 mounting holes to the Pipe. The distance between 1st & 3rd hole is the same as original design, so you only need to drill the middle hole. I included the nut traps & drill guide with this. Here is a video of it in motion. https://youtu.be/FxgOSKPxvdY I was a little off on the wrench holding hole, but is not worth me reprinting. If you want to adjust them some, change line 706
rotate([0,0,52-14.4]) //Change it to like 52-20
in the BoschMountRemix_Bottom_Rev34.scad You will loose a little bit of work area in either the X or Y axis with the vacuum attachment. The way my machine is configured, it is the X-axis I loose a little bit with.

Could not find anything online that matched what I wanted. Needed something stable for folders with lots of info, needed it tiered so you can clearly read the labels on every folder in the different areas so I made my first item. A little rough around the edges, I need to clean up a few of the joins on the objects as it didn't print perfect but it printed no problem. I even left it printing when I went to work and it finished fine! Could be scaled up 1.3 times if you need it slightly larger, I intend to print another with those settings and higher infill. You will see I have two designs of the same object. EDIT 1:
v.2 - small angled support for first tier
v.3 - generic cut out for order based management EDIT 2:
v.4 - Added 2 inches to height on most tiers, this helps thinner folders stay up right, expanded each tier by .4" in Y-axis so 2-3 folders can comfortably fit in each tier (more if they have few pages) Added angles to columns to help the folders lean. description.text:
I needed a piggy bank for my loose coins but I'm not crazy about pigs in the bedroom.  Traditional style - shake 'em out or break it.  With these, you can probably break it cleanly on a seam with a razor and superglue it back together a few times.  This is a ~5" sphere (200mm) and holds a lot.  If you want something smaller, I suggest scaling it by 0.8 for 4" or 0.6 for 3".  
Christmas tip - print smaller ones for your children, fill them up with loose change throughout the year, and then give them the spheres under the tree.  
This is printable, but it may be a challenge and the top won't be as clean (see photo).  For appearance, the pyramid (thing:105742) may be a better choice.  
Update note - I'd recommend printing this at 0.8 size, not full size, (about 4") to go with the pyramid.  Should make it slightly easier to print.

Scale to 0.8 size - better companion to the pyramid.

This is a second post of this thing. The first attempt contained 2 gears which were sized incorrectly. The inner gear of this version has no bumps on the flat surface and the edges were left unsmoothed. There are also artifacts inside the inner gear from mods I made which do not effect the print at all. As a kid I enjoyed playing with a Spirograph but always found it frustrating when the gear popped out and ruined the drawing. I have tried a number of spirographs available here and they seem to do the same thing, so I made one for myself. I made a capture ring on the edge of the inner gear which prevents the rotating gear from slipping upward. I also made sure the holes fit a standard inexpensive ball point pen. The result is a lot easier to use and even more fun!
